            <creation>This story, with the short title "Healing of the Two-Faced Egyptian," is very old: the earliest PEMM manuscript* in which this story appears is from around <date>1404</date>.Originally composed in <placeName ref="LOC3010Ethiop">Ethiopia</placeName></creation>
            <abstract>
                <p>In Egypt, Mary came upon a man who had two faces. He asked her to heal him, and when she touched him, he instantly had the face of an ordinary person. When she asked him about the source of his affliction, he quoted a psalm that said, “Sinners are known from the womb.” Mary then told the man to repent for his sins, and he did so. He then returned home, and his people, awestruck, asked him how he’d been healed. When he told them, they gathered all those in the community with disabilities and diseases and went to see Mary. She healed them all.</p>
            </abstract>
